{{Quote|How can they not know they are clones?|Milo Strander, an unknowing GeNode|<ref name="Pax Empirica">{{StoryCite|story=Pax Empirica&mdash;The Wookiee Annihilation|book=Star Wars: Galactic Battlegrounds: Prima's Official Strategy Guide}}</ref>}}
A '''GeNode''' was an [[Bioengineering/Legends|genetically engineered]] life form through the process by modified [[Arkanian/Legends|Arkanian]] [[Cloning/Legends|cloning]] technology. These specimens were drawn from at least three physically distinct genetic [[Clone template/Legends|templates]] and were intended to be a new wave of [[Stormtrooper/Legends|stormtroopers]] for the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]] during its early [[Imperial Era/Legends|reign]] and developed individual personalities, but they were characterized by a conditioned lack of awareness of their own nature as artificial life forms and lack of ability to communicate with fellow GeNodes on the subject of genetic engineering, setting them apart from the [[clone stormtrooper]]s. 

After the [[Declaration of a New Order|rise]] of the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]] in [[19 BBY/Legends|19 BBY]], the GeNode program was began by its [[Stormtrooper Corps/Legends|Stormtrooper Corps]] during its first [[Standard year/Legends|years]] before genetical engineering fell out of favor due to the instability of their conditioning and possible incite of the artificial [[Soldier/Legends|soldier]]s to a [[Clone madness|violent rage]], with their clone brethren as targets.

==Characteristics==
{{Quote|What are they, half droid?|Stormtrooper [[Wayson Dower]], on his GeNode superiors|<ref name="Pax Empirica" />}}
[[File:Stormtrooper-CotF.jpg|thumb|left|250px|At one time, nearly half of all stormtroopers were reputedly genetically engineered.]]
Unlike the [[Cloning/Legends|clone]] [[Clone trooper/Legends|troopers]]<ref name="TCW">{{TCW|Ambush}}</ref> modeled on [[Clone template/Legends|prime clone]] [[Jango Fett/Legends|Jango Fett]] and fielded by the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]] during the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]], the [[Soldier/Legends|soldiers]] known as GeNodes were unaware that they were clones. Conditioned with an inability to discuss their genetical enhancement with others, great resilience, and unflinching obedience,<ref name="Warfare">''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]''</ref> GeNodes developed distinct personalities and varying degrees of military competence but nonetheless did not leave service.<ref name="Pax Empirica" />

The conditioning blinding GeNodes to their biotech status, even when looking and communicating with others of the same template,<ref name="Pax Empirica" /> was not always successful, and its failure yielded disastrous results; soldiers suddenly found themselves surrounded by identical impostors sharing their face and would turn on their fellow clones in fits of fearful rage.<ref name="Warfare" />

One early GeNode clone line, part of the first generation of [[Bioengineering/Legends|genetically enhanced]] marines, had harsh faces and temperaments and [[Color/Legends|black]] [[Hair/Legends|hair]]. Later templates included a strongly built batch with deep blue [[Eye/Legends|eyes]] and thick blonde hair and a set of clones with wiry builds and small [[Bone/Legends|bones]], ideally suited to serve as [[Speeder bike/Legends|speeder bike]]&ndash;mounted [[Scout/Legends|scouts]].<ref name="Pax Empirica" />

==History==
{{Quote|So what if you did have to fight one?''"<br />"''A cloned soldier? No problem, they're not so tough.|Dower and Strander weigh their odds against their GeNode sergeants.|<ref name="Pax Empirica" />}}
[[File:Younger_Arca_Jeth.jpg|thumb|right|150px|The Arkanians produced the cloning methods that were the basis of GeNode technology.]]
GeNode [[Bioengineering/Legends|bioengineering]] was developed as a refinement of clone techniques employed by the [[Arkanian/Legends|Arkanians]],<ref name="Warfare" /> who were known for their endeavors in genetic science. During the Clone Wars, the [[Terrorist/Legends|terrorist]] and master geneticist [[Zeta Magnus]], himself the product of Arkanian experimentation, held control over an accelerated GeNode facility on<ref name="SkyeWalkers">''[[SkyeWalkers: A Clone Wars Story]]''</ref> the [[Planet/Legends|planet]]<ref name="TEA">''[[The Essential Atlas]]''</ref> [[Dantooine/Legends|Dantooine]]<ref name="SkyeWalkers" /> in [[22 BBY/Legends|22 BBY]].<ref name="SkyeWalkersDate">''[[SkyeWalkers: A Clone Wars Story]]'' takes place between {{Film|II}} and the [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' film]], both of which ''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]'' dates to [[22 BBY/Legends|22 BBY]].</ref> GeNode soldiers were fielded by the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]] following its [[Declaration of a New Order|establishment]] in [[19 BBY/Legends|19 BBY]].<ref name="Warfare" />

Before [[0 BBY/Legends|0 BBY]],<ref name="PaxEmpiricaDate">According to ''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]'', "[[Pax Empirica—The Wookiee Annihilation]]" takes place before {{Film|IV}}, which the book dates to [[0 BBY/Legends|0 BBY]].</ref> production of the dark-haired first generation template had long been discontinued, though some of these GeNodes continued to serve, including three [[Sergeant/Legends|sergeants]]&mdash;[[Tak Bazierre]], [[Dalia (clone)|Dalia]], and [[Oswald Strepp]]&mdash;in Imperial [[Captain/Legends|Captain]] [[Janzor]]'s [[Platoon/Legends|platoon]]. By this point, the light-haired template, exemplified by [[Corporal/Legends|Corporal]] [[Milo Strander]] and [[Private/Legends|Private]] [[Sterns Yennich]], accounted for forty percent of the Imperial [[Stormtrooper Corps/Legends|Stormtrooper Corps]]. Strander, unknowingly a GeNode himself, viewed the clones with disdain.<ref name="Pax Empirica" />

However, GeNode [[Bioengineering/Legends|genetically enhanced]] life forms fell out of favor with the [[Imperial Military/Legends|Imperial Military]] due to the instability resulting from the failure of their conditioning, and recruited [[Human/Legends|humans]] came to dominate the [[Stormtrooper/Legends|stormtroopers']] ranks.<ref name="Warfare" />

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|I rejected the idea that the GeNodes were a major source of clones for the Stormtrooper Corps, but I did want to acknowledge them&mdash;and, I hope, honor the spirit of an intriguing story.|Jason Fry|<ref name="WarfareEndnotes">{{Tumblr|subdomain=jasonfry|url=post/23478493322/eg-to-warfare-endnotes-pt-8|name=Jason Fry's Dorkery|text=EG to Warfare: Endnotes Pt. 8}}</ref>}}
[[File:PrimaSWGB.jpg|thumb|right|250px|"Pax Empirica" introduced GeNodes in the pages of the strategy guide.]]
GeNodes first appeared in "[[Pax Empirica—The Wookiee Annihilation]]," a short story by [[Steven L. Kent]] published in ''[[Star Wars: Galactic Battlegrounds: Prima's Official Strategy Guide]]'' in [[2001]],<ref name="Pax Empirica" /> prior to the release of the [[2002]] [[prequel trilogy]] film, [[Star Wars: Episode II Attack of the Clones|''Star Wars'': Episode II ''Attack of the Clones'']]. "Pax Empirica" references the presence of clones&mdash;the GeNodes&mdash;in the ranks of the Empire's stormtroopers, unusually for a story published prior to the introduction of that film's [[Grand Army of the Republic/Legends|clone army]],<ref name="ERC">''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]''</ref> portrayed subsequently as sharing a single genetic template and being aware of their common nature.<ref name="TCW" /> [[Jason Fry]], co-author of [[2012]]'s ''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]'',<ref name="Warfare" /> found the story's depiction of clones at odds with such later revelations and therefore worked to downplay the presence of GeNodes in the Stormtrooper Corps in the [[Star Wars: Essential Guides|''Essential Guide'']].<ref name="WarfareEndnotes" />

An editorial footnote submitted to [[Lucasfilm]] by [[Abel G. Peña]] with his novella ''[[SkyeWalkers: A Clone Wars Story]]'' identifies the GeNode chamber mentioned in that work as the cloning facility depicted in ''[[Galaxy of Fear: Clones]]'',<ref name="SkyewalkersEndnotes">{{Blogspot|subdomain=abelgpena|url=2019/12/skyewalkers-clone-wars-story.html|name=The Philodoxer|text=SkyeWalkers: A Clone Wars Story Footnotes/Endnotes, Part 4—Claustrophobic Clones, Imperial Vs. Metric, and Xenu's Paradox|date=2019-12-18}}</ref> a [[1998]] juvenile novel written by [[John Whitman]],<ref name="ERC" /> but the connection is not apparent in the text as published<ref name="SkyeWalkers" /> in [[2015]].<ref name="JCF">{{JCFCite|url=posts/52204636|board=Literature|thread=Abel G. Peña's "Skyewalkers" and "Lone Wolf"|user=[[John Hazlett|jSarek]]|date=2015-05-11|time=8:59 PM|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160831095014/http://boards.theforce.net/threads/abel-g-pe%C3%B1as-skyewalkers-and-lone-wolf.50027998/}}</ref>

